latestPosts.caption:
This is 43 💃🏽 Gratitude is my word for 2024 🫶🏽 I’ve fully realized that each and every single day is a gift, a blessing.  Aging is a luxury and a privilege. I’m honestly so grateful for another trip around the sun ☀️ I’m at a place in my life where for quite some time, I’ve solely focused on taking care of others 🤍

However, 43 is going to be a year where I prioritize how I can help myself become the best version of me.  Because honestly the past two decades have been a bit of a self-loathing era. And I most definitely want to change that 💁🏽‍♀️ 

Wearing alternative hair definitely helped me love and accept myself more but 43 is for going in deeper and doing the damn work 🙌🏽 So, here’s a toast to 43 my FUCK YOU year 🥂 FUCK YOU to all the things that brought me negativity, sorrow, anger, pain, shame and guilt.  I’m working on the best version of me for 43 and I know I can only go up from here ⬆️ 

#wearthehair #femalehairloss #thriving #womensupportingwomen

latestPosts.caption: Meet Lorena 🤍 Ever since high school, I can remember being self-conscious about my thin hair. Throughout graduate school and significant life events, I noticed my hair would shed drastically during particular times of the year. To take proactive measures, I went to a dermatologist in my 20s, and they assured me I just had thin hair and that I did not need to worry since hair loss didn’t run in my family. Whatever kind of reassurance that was supposed to give me, I didn’t find comfort in. Then I had my two boys, and postpartum took a toll on my hair. I remember feeling so helpless and hopeless watching all the hair fall. Round 2 at the dermatologist and after a biopsy this time it resulted in either AGA or Telogen Effluvium. They were pretty sure it was TE since AGA did not run in my family. I was devastated and felt so lost. I was told by my medical professionals to just try to relax, not to worry so much. The most challenging part about living with hair loss while still having hair is just how misunderstood you feel most of the time. I would look in the mirror terrified, stress over every strand that fell, and just be constantly preoccupied with my hair. It consumed my life, drained, and depleted me. I could not focus on anything else other than hair. When I tried to share my concerns with loved ones, such as my mom or a friend, they would just tell me I was crazy or that I was making a bigger deal of it than it really was. It was heartbreaking, going through something and not feeling seen or heard. I personally didn’t know anyone going through something similar. I constantly scanned other women’s hairlines, obsessed over their hair, and constantly wished I had better hair. Then, as a godsend, I discovered the world of alternative hair on social media. I saw women just like me, living their best lives, looking so confident and beautiful and sharing all about the wigs and toppers that helped them achieve this. I thought to myself I can do this. If they can do it, why not me? **Continued in comments 🙈**

✨ It’s not about them,  it’s about you. ✨

I used to stress so much about what people might think when I first started wearing wigs.
“Will they like it?” “Can they tell it’s a wig?” “ Do they think it looks good?
Sound familiar?

But over time, I realized something powerful:
The only opinion that truly matters is mine.
If I feel confident, beautiful, and like me — then that’s more than enough. 🤍

Choosing a wig is personal. It’s part of your healing, your confidence, your story.
So wear that new style proudly.  Because YOU are the one who has to feel good in it not anyone else. 💁🏽‍♀️

latestPosts.caption:
The worst part about wearing wigs in the summer? 

You guessed it 🥵 the heat! Living in Miami, where the heat and humidity are no joke during the summer months, my trick is hopping from AC to AC, wearing as little clothing as possible 🤭 and always carrying a fan. Wearing your hair up also helps a lot.

Next up: hurr envy 🙄 It definitely hits harder in the summer. I find myself more prone to envy women I see at the beach or pool. Envying those who ladies that don’t need to wear wigs and have healthy, shiny, thick hair even when it’s wet or sweaty. But even with those feelings, I feel incredibly blessed and grateful to have the option to wear wigs. They help me feel more confident and secure especially poolside.

And finally feeling limited 🫠 Not being able to participate in certain activities while wearing a wig can be tough. When I’m at the beach, pool, or water park with my kids, I can’t wear my nice human hair wigs. They’re an investment, and things like sun, sunscreen, saltwater, and chlorine can cause serious damage. So, I know going into these activities that I need to leave my favorite pieces at home and that can feel limiting.

But over time, you learn to problem solve and adapt. That’s the beauty of being part of this amazing hair loss community: we share tips, tricks, and support for all kinds of situations 🫶🏽
